SIMPLE: flagrant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flagrant
<hw>Fla"grant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>flagrans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>flagrate</ets> to
burn, akin to Gr. <?/: cf. F. <ets>flagrant</ets>. Cf. <er>Flame</er>,
<er>Phlox</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Flaming; inflamed; glowing;
burning; ardent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The beadle's lash still <qex>flagrant</qex> on their back.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A young man yet <qex>flagrant</qex> from the lash of the
executioner or the beadle.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Flagrant</qex> desires and affections.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Actually in preparation, execution, or performance;
carried on hotly; raging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A war the most powerful of the native tribes was
<qex>flagrant</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Palfrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Flaming into notice; notorious; enormous; heinous;
glaringly wicked.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Atrocious; flagitious; glaring. See
<er>Atrocious</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flagrantly</ent>⟦br⟧
